Changing someone with genocide for killing a few hundred or even a few thousand people ... would mean that what just happened in Najaf, or earlier in Fallujah, was genocide.

Legally, that's incorrect. Under international law, killing people because of their ethnicity, especially if it's inteneded to have an impact on the group as a whole, is genocide, regardless of the numbers involved.

Some are uncomfortable with that and believe that the charge of genocide should be reserved only for those cases where the death toll is such as to threaten the existence of the group (which is how we generally think of it).

Others reply that limiting it to such an extreme case effectively ends the possibility of prosecution: Even Hitler could have gotten off the hook of a charge of genocide against Jews by pointing to their presence in other countries beyond his reach and saying that therefore he was not actually a threat to their existence as a people.
(cont.)
