Comparing various recent claims of numbers of victims, I think there are important differences, but these point to graver errors than lying about numbers.

Look at Bosnia: exhumations and *discoveries* of mass graves continue to this day - 18,000 found, 25,000 people still missing. Last I heard, in Srebrenica alone, numbers of corpses found climbed above 6,000, nearing original claims of 7,000. And among the 100+ discovered recently in a cave near Foca, were ones to put the lie to persistent denials that camps where Bosnian Serbs held people were cruel concentration camps.

So, if there are lots of killed and there *is* a concerted effort to dig up graves, the work still takes years to decades. In Iraq, where not all evidence for genocide comes from the US govt &amp; friends, there was no such effort - the real outrage in the 5,000 number is not that victims' numbers were bloated, but that the occupying power didn't spend a cent on finding &amp; exhuming mass graves in an orderly way.
